However, it is not yet won.
In fact, congressmen must complete some of the details of the agreement before they can release and vote on the final form of the bill.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed at the House of Representatives on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the House Committee on Banking and Financial Services, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
The Senate, according to sources, could probably vote on the plan on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first major psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
However, thereafter, it will be "cut-cut" by the complexity of the mechanisms to help markets achieve in practice.
Paulson: Plan must be effective
"We've made a lot of progress.
We have solved our differences of opinion on what the shape of the package to stabilise the market should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be reached later on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday to give the final shape to the government's fund.
This should buy back from financial corporations for non-negotiable mortgage assets that pull financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the brink of a definitive agreement of the plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue the recovery plan, but I think we're there," Paulson said.
Signal for Asian trading
The global financial crisis is hitting stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the non-GaTA senator Harry Reid, legislators are thus trying to reach a final agreement in Congress later on Sunday.
Indeed, they want to reassure investors before trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone, where Congress's decision could affect Monday's trading.
But it is not yet clear with certainty when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote on the bill, nor whether they can't get a last-minute negotiation stuck on a problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be passed in the next few days.
But the law will still undergo a number of changes.
The total amount to be aided to the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be available as soon as possible, as requested by President George Bush.
