The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for the directors participating in the programme and sets up a committee to supervise the fund.
This should be run by the Treasury Department.
"We have worked very hard at this and have made great progress towards a deal that will work and will be useful for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also envisages assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new repayments for the mortgages it will buy in order to reduce the monthly hire purchase costs for borrowers and allow them to keep their houses.
Marek: Psychological help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to David Mark, the chief economist of Patria Finance, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"And that's because it's not known by what mechanism and at what price the problem assets will be purchased.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government will split the losses between them," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be approved now or at the start of next week is not all that important, according to Mark.
"More importantly, this week's congressmen agree to support the plan and to sanction it as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement on the fact that approval will take place is the most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
The triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, with a combined total of 29 percent
The noticeable weakening of the two parties of the previous grand coalition and the significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties was brought about by Sunday's early parliamentary elections in Austria, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly strong losses, with the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer shaking up seriously.
In contrast, the election leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider is planning a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the strongest party in the country of social democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest party with 29.8 percent of the vote, but it loses 5.5 percent of the vote against the latest elections in 2006.
The ÖVP fared even worse, losing almost nine per cent of the vote with 25.6 per cent.
These are the worst results of both of these major parties in Austria's post-war history and, especially for the Peoples who called for the early elections, a literally disastrous result.
As recently as the beginning of July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead in their preferences over the SPÖ.
But voters apparently punished them for letting the government fail.
Early reactions to the results were speculated about the possible resignation of the party's chairman and incumbent vice-chancellor, Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday at a special meeting of the party's bureau.
Such a development would probably facilitate the path to the still most likely way out of the election result, the renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ), they received a preliminary 18 percent of the vote and the BZÖ eleven per cent - the Social Democrats also voiced concerns about the repetition of the years in 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (then the FPÖ was unified, in 2005, it was split from the BZÖ) in a joint government that even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Haider is clearly betting on this development, having already said he was ready to work with any party and anticipates a return to Vienna for national politics.
The Green Party was still in the parliament, but it lost easily and fell between the Austrian political parties from third to fifth.
Neither of the other parties apparently surpassed the 4% threshold and made it to parliament.
