The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet we are missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classic ones cheaper.
He may not be missed for long.
We have written about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe at Mobil.cz many times.
Indeed, this was confirmed by ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS in our country is higher than in the rest of the Union.
Following the European Commission's latest steps in the field of regulating roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may be: for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to go into battle.
It may sound paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetrating up to 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecoms Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák often rings in this, who has commented several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network does not seem to have much chance (after all, it would be hard to find frequencies anymore).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant price reduction, to which even classical operators had to respond.
At the same time, before the entry of the pike like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar voices in the UK as in the UK.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we don't have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, the operator has managed to recruit more than 100,000 customers and become the country's fifth largest operator.
At the same time, the financial group Penta, which owns U:fona, among others, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, they only need far fewer customers than a classical operator.
They do not entail the relatively high cost of the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators tend to profile themselves as low-cost - offering cheap calls and SMS, but this is often counterbalanced by a closer service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as much as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilelogisation in Poland shows, a bet on a novel target group can also be a pretty good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
"Security guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating in this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept could be caught up in our country.
Vodafone's press spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Rather, it will be launched by Mobileping in other countries of our region," Jana Studničková, press spokesperson for the financial group Penta, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
It impresively confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are certainly not in favour of this idea.
Rather the opposite, they try to do their best to prevent any potential competitor from being created.
The interest in launching a virtual mobile operator has not been hared by the GTS Novera group for a long time, which would like to take the next step to become a real competitor to Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer sector.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer not only fixed telecommunications services to our customers, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to make progress in the negotiations with some of them," says the group's press spokesperson, Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe there's a glimmer of better days.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be looking forward to perhaps by the end of the year.
For the time being, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room for a fully-fledged virtual operator to be created on the Czech market.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, no entity has approached us with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň of the Telefónica O2 press department said in his comments to Mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is also invoked by other operators.
T-Mobile's press spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet recorded any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to be further built."
He adds: "It is difficult for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we'd have to have a concrete agreement on the table to consider in this short term."
Vodafone is more likely to focus its attention on its own 3G licence requirements.
Miroslav Čepický says: "By negotiating with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of burden and infrastructure sharing.
We consider this to be the most beneficial in terms of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The progress of mobile operators is easy to understand, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, leading to a fall in prices and thus a decline in their profits.
So why facilitate the emergence of such a competitor?
The fact that when operators are at a loss, they can pull together, is also evidenced by the tussle over the formation of the U:fona.
Perhaps the biggest pressure towards ČTÚ was at the time of the creation of U:fona from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
But now it is U:fon who fits as an argument for not allowing a virtual operator to.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive mobile market environment was recently amplified by the entry of a fourth mobile operator to the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player would make high demands on him and, above all, his services."
However, given this approach by the mobile operators, the sheer complete disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is a striking one.
This is not just the position of ČTÚ, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in competition.
These are exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stance on the whole issue.
"A virtual operator's entry into the mobile market would be possible after a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the lease of the necessary infrastructure were concluded.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential bidders was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," Kristián Chalupa from the External Relations Department of the OOHS said in response to our question.
The comments thus formulated will come as no surprise to the representatives of the operators.
It is more from the authority, which is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position in the market, it is more than a precarious one.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the country, where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their market entry has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services."
But the pressure to properly operate the market environment and the price drop are not among the interests of the OBR.
In fact, the shocking thing about the case is the touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is entirely self-evident.
Like the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations, it is surely just a matter of chance and a tough competitive fight.
"The office did not find any signs of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore has no adequate increased responsibility for its market conduct.
The necessary tools to open the mobile market for virtual operators are most likely missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his comments.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets produced by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market in terms of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators have a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer a different perspective - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically, has a monopoly on its network.
So in a segment, it necessarily has to be dominant.
But even if we did not allow this argument, it should be minimally cautionary tale for the OBR that the three mobile operators are doing strikingly similarly.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The upload of responsibility at ČTÚ is then a rather common trick in telecommunications, with the ÚOHS taking its hands off the whole affair.
We've met him on several occasions like this.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of ČTÚ's powers to competition in telecommunications failed to enforce, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the OHS must know this more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It goes when no one is watching
At the same time, the operation of some pseudo-ovirtual operators, of which there are several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
It is usually about multilevel marketing companies.
It offers its own mobile phone services, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach the elect.
The magic is that the company acts as a classic corporate customer to the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer, they will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators forbid a similar reschance.
"If there were cases of which you are talking about, it could be a violation of the contractual terms that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová said in response to our question on the problem.
But it is unlikely that such action would be brought to accountable to responsible people from mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is opposed to such a procedure.
They make significant profits from the activities of these firms, and yet - unlike actual virtual operators - they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, however, the services of these companies are used by only a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot dispose of it fully as ordinary customers of mobile operators."
But that is what should be at least strange to ČTÚ.
In addition, another question is being raised for the OBR.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the OBR has quite strong powers to detect such an activity, and if it does not want to, it may not be content with the operators' explanation that they have no idea about this and their terms of trade prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As the text has already been mentioned several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable decline in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually every country where virtual operators were created, the classical operators tried to hinder their creation more or less.
The arguments used by them were virtually identical - too small, or perhaps too saturated, quality problems of service, etc.
But it was in these early countries that regulators intervened at these moments, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but of their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they then achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and others pack in on it.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are tossing the case around like a hot potato.
We cannot escape the perception in our experience that ambiguity in the competencies is more than suited to them in these cases.
But let's not throw a gun in the Rye.
If behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator will really appear in our country soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving up again.
If one of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the OBR to remain indifferent to reject (discrimination) of other candidates.
And we may stop calling for more than in the rest of Europe.
