William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary for William Woodruff (September 25) claims that he "return to the economic history of Oxford in 1946 and became a researcher at Houblon-Norman in 1950... and also studied at BSc, MA and PhD."
This is based on Woodruff's author's remark in the Beyond Nab End, but it's not accurate.
From 1946 to 1953 he taught economic history at the University of Nottingham, and at that time he finished his dissertation on the British rubber industry, led by Professor J. D. Chambers, and subsequently published in 1958 as a publication by the British Rubber Industry.
He actually spent the years 1950-51 in America as a researcher at Houblon-Norman and the summer of 1952 at the Illinois, Harvard and New York University.
In 1953, he finally left Nottingham and moved to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff passed this part of his career.
