"Auto bee" prevents precipitation
Nissan was inspired to make progress in the development of accident technologies in nature, specifically with bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes bee flying as a model, thus preventing collisions.
Such is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
Engineers of the Center for Technical Progress Nissan Motor Co. robot developed in collaboration with the Centre for Progress in the University of Japan's science and technology research.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology, Research and Development of the Brand, BR23C is presented as an extension of the Nissan Security Shire of the Four Hazan Safety Shires.
The robot is designed to strengthen the precipitation preference capacity for the brand's cars.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which closely resembles the Nissan's safety shield.
But the most important are the folded bee's eyes, which are able to be seen in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees, which the yacht allows the whip to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual feature, the engineers designed what they called the Laser Range Finder.
It records obstacles that are located up to two metres within a 180-degree radius of the BR23C, calculate the distance of the object and sends out the signal to the on-board micro-processor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment the obstacle is recorded, the robot mimics the bee movements and immediately changes the direction by turning the wheels into the right or even larger angle to prevent the collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that all evasive maneuvers are perfectly instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and the main engineer of this project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move up and downwards or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction that is allowed to rotate its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and capabilities as for bees.
Nissan, therefore, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, used the rotation function to prevent the robots from colliding.
"The facility only needs to process the information every few seconds and act according to these figures.
It does not require preserving information or logical intuitions from previous maneuvers, which allows it to function without interruption with just two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we don't talk about the gig or the mega at the memory.'
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for immediate precipitation prevention, a technology for which Nissan predicts to be used in aerial cars in a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to install the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would take the driver to the target while avoiding obstacles on the road.
