The Interior Ministry is demanding that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol should have to install a system in his car to prevent him from starting the car while drunk or if he is not in a breather.
The proposal became known in June of this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme Prosecutor's Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will take one year.
His goal is to return the driver behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to take a course for the transport re-education.
In addition to the National Transportation Security Office, the Directorate-General for Transport of Transport and the Foundation of the Technological Institute for the Safety of Automobile Transport and the Foundation of the Institute of Automobile Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between the 30 and 75% of the car drivers accused more than once in this condition will be behind the wheel again in this condition.
Alcolock should prevent this as it is a system connected to a vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the exhaled air and prevents the car from being started if the driver is not breathing before or if it is recorded higher than the permitted alcohol concentration.
Its price exceeds EUR 1 000 and it would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study conducted in this sense in the US in 2007 showed that for vehicles equipped with this equipment, offences had decreased by 65 % in the first year of introduction.
In Spain, it is expected that 115 people could save the lives of 115 people each year.
The measure is limited to administrative penalties for two reasons: to address this behaviour before resulting in a criminal offence.
And to help its implementation, as the legislation can be implemented in the usual way, but the necessary legislation of the criminal provisions requires an amendment to the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any of the sales versions, although it has already been installed in some industrial cars and public service vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on the PSOE (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party) proposal, recommending that it be used to install the system on school buses, as is the case in France.
