Opinions - Orwellian discourse by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian Mining Company Barrick Gold.
With the Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched the prosecution of three authors and a poor libel publishing house to incite a "transparent public debate" and is demanding six million.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of prosecution for an insult to honour, but a law.
It is no surprise that Garver completely misses this crucial distinction.
Or is it for Barrick Gold the best way to have a public debate to break up anyone who would dare to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome of the process, the author and publisher of the book Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend and fight in a highly unbalanced fight with an army of attorneys supported by the nearly bottomless pockets of the mining company.
The tactics in these unbalanced fights, moreover, often consistin in the degrading of the defendants in order to enforce the conciliation procedure, which will be floundered by the mouth of the opposing party and, moreover, by anyone who dared to pursue the matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view to the matter to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate in normal circumstances lies in the exchange of ideas and not in baton blows.
The mining company was therefore not enough to open its books, its documentation and establish a real debate through newspapers, the media, publications and funding of independent science teams that could bring light to the matter.
Barrick Gold, however, seems to have no confidence in public opinion and rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of the book Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate" while despising the views of the same public?
This word in the vice-president's world seems to refer to only bold-paying attorneys, and not all Canadians; that is a rather narrowed concept of the term.
In a democracy, even the libelers have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public, which supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and consider the matter, but on the basis of a civilised exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant's mouth is to be clogged (in the framework of its prosecution of the "public debate" Barrick, incidentally, has just given an official notice to the authors of Noir Canada to officially inform them that they should stop using this term...).
Aside from the surreal speech by Garver, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on university freedom of inquiry and the search for truth that is essential for any democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to quote credible sources and to the debate on the facts and interpretations that themselves form the basis of intellectual activity.
In a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are not to be liked by the rich firms of this world without exposing ourselves to the repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have been created if it had followed the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has the right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's overreacting clearly shows that, despite what he claims, he has no appetite for having a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to introduce measures to limit such a type of unauthorized prosecution.
