Yesterday, the Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement on the biggest economic bailout plan since the Great Crisis of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use US$700 billion to hinder the financial crisis that has been clouding Wall Street for months now must still be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of the chosen representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money imposed, new measures to capture the number of houses seized for defaults, as well as the right to monitor the level of wages paid to executives of rescued firms.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican official at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, following the end of the two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and come to an agreement that is effective in the markets," said Bush administration official, Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done in such a way that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis currently taking place on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"That's a crucial point: if we don't do it, the trauma, the chaos, and disruption of Americans' daily lives will be enormous," said Jad Gregg, a Republican.
Over the past few hours, the negotiations have started at maximum speed for fear of the effect of further failures on the investor's mood.
The set time limit was the opening of the markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US presidency were invited to the negotiations later, and both were more likely to comment on the deal, but without rebutting their dissatisfaction, saying it had to be resorted to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited the addition of an agreement on certain measures, in particular the aim of enabling the owners of residence to be retained, and the wage measures for leading labor-saved companies.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate themselves on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on the TV's waves.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, who was questioned by another station on whether to vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features I have read [demonstrate] that it is something that we will all have to digest and use to move on.
Choosing inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The $700bn plan aims to buy back doubtful and risky and non-sale assets of US financial institutions with taxpayers' money.
The plan comes after a 14-month crisis set up by the bursting of the housing market bubble, which first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in a cash freeze and a breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
The fall of last week's first draft agreement was caused by Republican members.
Ever since the Democrats agreed to the government's liability for some of the "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty, but not to buy them, it is believed that the impasse is being averted.
In an effort to approximate conflicting views in Congress, a measure has been added to the government to allow the government to introduce new fees to help it get its deposit back if, as a result of the program, it has to take losses for five years.
The new plan envisages a first-purpose of the first amount of 250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire stakes in rescued firms that will pay him dividends in the event of a profit and which he will be able to resell when it is over.
The federal government will be able to delay the seizure procedures for the loans associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as setting limits on the level of the evaluation and compensation paid to the executives of the affected firms.
The architects of the plan would like to vote in the House of Representatives to the House of Representatives on Wednesday and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain that their plan will be green.
Yesterday, votes continued to rise against this project in both the Republican and Democratic camp.
"It's very clear that Washington can't hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, addressing voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But earning money in the taxpayer is not the solution."
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the "Skeptics Committee" listens to the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Afour hundred esteemed economics professors, among them three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: we ask Congress not to rush in too much and to examine the path of study," he said yesterday.
At the same time, it was reaffirmed in Europe that this crisis was a world crisis.
Following the end of the extraordinary meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of Fortis, the banking group, for €11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, who is on the verge of collapse since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) in the wake of the crisis in risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is one of Europe's 20 largest banks and the top ten insurers.
"We will not lose this money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In return, we get the right to vote in the bank and influence.
