The psychology of trumping: why are we spending more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been uncovered by researchers in the field of neurology and economics at the University of New York.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to lag behind in the eBay auction competition, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
The research was used by an experimental auction to map out a diagram of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers grated, the other group participated in a staged auction, using the MRI Method of Mertical Misconance to examine the active areas of the brains of the experimental people.
In both games, the participants could have won the money, but in the game at the auction, the important element of which is to outmanecele, the whole, under the cerebral cortex, called striatum, began to work intensively in the loss.
In addition to many other functions, this brain area plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
The ungodification of the price is therefore possible, according to the researchers, to be explained by the effort to avoid the stride reaction of the striata.
To shore up their theory, members of the research team from the economists' ranks conducted a financial cross-cutting investigation.
Under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the group were promised that if they emerged victorious, they would receive an extra $15.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members lost that money as well.
The difference between the two groups was all about one being emphasized by a win and another for losing.
Members of the group playing "against the loss," of course, were willing to go higher than they were in the control and "victorious" group, which confirms the neurologists' hypothesis.
"These results cannot be inferred from any pre-existing economic theory.
They have until now explained the phenomena observable at auctions by the joys of victory and the avoidance of risk.
It was the neurological imaging methods that helped us resolve the contradiction between the two theories by now arriving at a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the University of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Approximately half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, while in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed as the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only 7,000 of them are being treated. The cause is that the sick often don't know they're infected.
The name of hepatitis is a summary of the affluence of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, the liver and jaundice inflammation is characterised, but the agents of the disease and the diseases they cause are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruss spread by two mainstreams, depending on the origins of the disease: hepatitis A and E digestive tract (for example, by in-infected food, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses in the blood and bodily fluids (sperm, ashes, saline).
In any case, travelers should be protected by vaccinating A and B, the vaccine does not exist against the C virus.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after taking the infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, urges to vomit.
The skin and the whites of the eyes form a jaundice, a lightened stool and darken the urine. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people die worldwide from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that only one in ten of the infected is treated with medication.
hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of the infected are not even aware of their illnesses, the agents of the disease are destroying liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms do not come in many cases for up to 20-30 years.
It is therefore very important to prevent early, to carry out regular depotism.
In three groups, the disease occurs a lot more often than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, between drug users and tattooing people.
Currently, the projected global number of individuals infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
As the disease can already be shown by a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his or her general practitioner if he or she has recorded any sign of unknown origin.
When detected early, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the organism to prevent contagion and prevent cancer from occurring.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, which was organised by the organisations with the sufferers for the world for the first time in 2004.
It aims to draw attention to chronic liver inflammation caused by these viruses, the causes of its origin and the importance of early detection of the disease.
